<li id="cite_note-Craddock_N_p.109-59"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Craddock_N_p.109_59-7"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation journal">Craddock N, Owen MJ (2010). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2815936">"The Kraepelinian dichotomy&#160;– going, going... But still not gone"</a>. <i>The British Journal of Psychiatry</i> <b>196</b> (2): 92–95. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//dx.doi.org/10.1192%2Fbjp.bp.109.073429">10.1192/bjp.bp.109.073429</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Central" title="PubMed Central">PMC</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2815936">2815936</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" title="PubMed Identifier" class="mw-redirect">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20118450">20118450</a>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASchizoaffective+disorder&amp;rft.atitle=The+Kraepelinian+dichotomy%26nbsp%3B%E2%80%93+going%2C+going...+But+still+not+gone&amp;rft.au=Craddock+N%2C+Owen+MJ&amp;rft.aulast=Craddock+N%2C+Owen+MJ&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC2815936&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1192%2Fbjp.bp.109.073429&amp;rft_i